  <h2>Design decisions</h2>
  <h3>Rethinking information layout to create momentum</h3>
  <p>
    Consolidating all setup tasks into a single flow introduced a risk: information overload. To address this, we focused first on information architecture—deciding what to show and how much context users actually needed to take action. Through stakeholder alignment, we agreed that early task completion was more important than full user comprehension at this stage. In parallel, user research centered on a simple goal: did the experience feel easy and compelling enough to engage with? <strong>We ultimately landed on a progress‑focused design that reduced cognitive load while creating forward momentum</strong>, using the Zeigarnik Effect to encourage continued engagement without overwhelming users with detail.
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 tablet:grid-cols-3 gap-y-8 gap-x-[10%] mt-6 tablet:-mx-[10%]">
    <!-- Task focused -->
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <img src="/images/Setup Progress-Design process-task focused.png" alt="Task focused design exploration" class="w-[80%] mx-auto h-auto rounded-lg block" />
      <div class="text-xs text-gray-700">
        <p><strong>Task focused</strong> Show each task as a large card with full details, giving users immediate clarity without extra clicks—but at the cost of making it harder to see other task options at a glance.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <!-- Process focused -->
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <img src="/images/Setup Progress-Design process-process focused.png" alt="Process focused design exploration" class="w-[80%] mx-auto h-auto rounded-lg block" />
      <div class="text-xs text-gray-700">
        <p><strong>Process focused</strong> Visually emphasize the progress bar while displaying all tasks as simplified checkmark cards, maximizing the Zeigarnik Effect through visible progress—but with minimal task detail provided</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <!-- Overview -->
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <img src="/images/Setup Progress-Design process-Overview.png" alt="Overview design exploration" class="w-[80%] mx-auto h-auto rounded-lg block" />
      <div class="text-xs text-gray-700">
        <p><strong>Overview</strong> Show all tasks in a list view, with the next task expanded in a large detail card below—making progress visible and context clear, but at the risk of information overload and increased scrolling.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Finding the right visual tone between gamification and brand</h3>
  <p>
    We then refined the visual tone to introduce moments of delight and further support engagement. At the same time, we were mindful that this is a secondary task within productivity tool- the goal was assistance, not distraction. Through user testing learned that users preferred a calmer, more restrained tone consistent with Microsoft's brand. As a result, we focused on conveying progress through subtle, purposeful motion rather than overt game mechanics.
  </p>
  <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 tablet:grid-cols-3 gap-y-8 gap-x-[10%] mt-6 tablet:-mx-[10%]">
    <!-- Badge Status -->
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <img src="/images/Setup Progress-Design process-Badge status.png" alt="Badge status design exploration" class="w-[80%] mx-auto h-auto rounded-lg block" />
      <div class="text-xs text-gray-700">
        <p><strong>Badge Status</strong> Users earn badges and titles as they complete tasks. Best suited for multi-path journeys and varied achievements.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <!-- Completion loading -->
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <img src="/images/Setup Progress-Design process-Completion loading.png" alt="Completion loading design exploration" class="w-[80%] mx-auto h-auto rounded-lg block" />
      <div class="text-xs text-gray-700">
        <p><strong>Completion loading</strong> A color-filling trophy was explored as a completion metaphor, but it implied a reward that the tasks didn't actually deliver.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <!-- Process tracking -->
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <img src="/images/Setup Progress-Design process-Progress tracking.png" alt="Progress tracking design exploration" class="w-[80%] mx-auto h-auto rounded-lg block" />
      <div class="text-xs text-gray-700">
        <p><strong>Process tracking</strong> A check-mark animation with a bead completing the circle reinforced task progression while staying visually consistent with Microsoft 365's checklist patterns and calm productivity tone.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

